comments.body:
To reproduce the issue of an eni stuck in the detaching state you can use:

{code}
aid=$(euca-attach-network-interface -i i-d80de3f1 -d 1 eni-d902ade0) && sleep 2 && euca-detach-network-interface $aid
{code}

The issue is that the cached instance attachment information is not updated for use when comparing the attachment information from the cluster controller. The fix is to ensure the cloud controller updates its cached information before comparing with the incoming network interface attachment information.

Workarounds could be to shorten the touch interval for an instance (e.g. set cloud.vmstate.instance_touch_interval=1), or to modify an instance in some other way so that the incoming network interface attachment state is processed (bundle, attach eni or volume, modify instance termination protection, etc?). Using a short touch interval is not recommended on a cloud with many instances as it will cause performance issues.
